<br>
My first raid to the planes was with Clan Spiritslammer.  I was friends with a few members including the leader. But there just wasn't always room.  Each raid I didn't make the list but I showed up to the port spot (for Hate) and waited to be an alt if needed.  I wasn't needed until the 4th raid where someone didn't show so I got to go.  I also had alot of friends in Harpers.  I pretty much only raided with these two guilds for a long time.  I supported raids that weren't just fear where my armor was.  I went to more raids to Hate than I ever did for Fear.  So when a Fear raid was scheduled I was almost always given a spot.<br>
<br>
I then ran alot of raids.  I was very picky on who I took.  I didn't take just any random sign up.  If I didn't know the person, or a friend didn't recommend the person, they didn't go.  Most of my raids I took 36 people tops.  I almost always had 75+ people wanting to go, usually with 50 or so being friends.  Meaning I not only had to tell the 25 odd people I didn't know they couldn't go but also 15 or so friends that they couldn't go.  So a level 50 druid that I didn't know pretty much had NO chance of getting in a raid of mine unless for some really odd reason that none of my druid friends could make it.<br>
<br>
So ... the best thing to do is:<br>
<br>
1) See what guilds your friends are in.<br>
2) See when they raid and sign up to support ALL of their raids.  Not just fear, go to Hate and anywhere else they raid.<br>
3) Don't get upset and post comments about why weren't you included.  Its tough telling friends they can't go  and its really upsetting to have someone ranting you that you don't even know.<br>
4) Show up as an alt and wait patiently to see if you are needed.  Just let the leader know you are there as an alt if needed then sit there quietly.  Don't keep asking if there is room.<br>
5) Repeat.<br>
<br>
If you solo'd to 50 and don't really know anyone that raids ... I suggest you start grouping with more people and get to know them.  See which guilds your friends are in and try to meet more of them.  MOST raid leaders do not take strangers on raids.<br>
<br>
For most of my planar levels I was not in a high level guild.  Heck most of the time I was either Indy or guild leader of a very small guild.  I never had a problem raiding.  I think I averaged 3 planar raids a week.  For 2 months I raided every Fri/Sat/Sun.  It had nothing to do with being in a big guild.  It had everything to do with knowing and being friends with a bunch of people that held raids.  Most of those guilds weren't &quot;high level guilds&quot; either.<br>
<br>
If you have the skill, ability, and the right attitude you won't have a problem as long as you get to know people. <p><A HREF="http://www.silentredemption.org/" TARGET="_new">
